1991). ({{ISBN|0-8240-7975-2}}), short essays by scholars\n* Maisel, L. Sandy. ''American Political Parties and Elections: A Very Short Introduction'' (2007), 144 pp\n* O'Connor, Karen,  Larry J. Sabato, and Alixandra B. Yanus. ''American Government: American Government: Roots and Reform'' (11th ed. 2011)\n* Wilson, James Q.,  and John J. Diiulio and Meena Bose. ''American Government: Institutions and Policies'' (12th ed. 2010)\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Politics of the United States}}\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Society_and_Culture/Politics}}\n;Official party websites:\n*[http://www.democrats.org Official Democratic Party Web Site]\n*[http://www.gop.org Official Republican Party Web Site]\n*[http://www.greenpartyus.org Official Green Party Web Site]\n*[http://www.lp.org Official Libertarian Party Web Site]\n\n{{Politics in the United States}}\n{{North America topic|Politics of}}\n{{United States topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Politics Of The United States}}\n[[Category:Politics of the United States| ]]\n", "name_user": "71.241.159.31", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Corrected governmental form based on observable facts)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Politics_of_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "Ghar Ki Lakshmi Betiyann", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Ban ti pitin ki mank rol\n| image                = Betiyaan.jpg\n| caption              =\n| picture_format       = [[576i]]\n| runtime              = approximately 23 minutes\n| creator              = [[Creative Eye Limited]]\n| director             = Rajan Shahi<br>Romesh Kalra<br>Sunand Kumar Baranwal<br>\n                         Santosh Bhatt\n| producer             = {{ubl|Dheeraj Kumar|Zuby Kochhar}}\n| company              = [[Creative Eye Limited]]\n| starring             = [[Kshitee Jog]] <br> [[Aleeza Khan]] <br> Smriti Mohan <br> [[Gunjan Walia]] <br> [[Soni Singh]]                             \n| opentheme            = \"Ghar Ki Lakshmi Betiyann\" \n| country              = India\n| language             = [[Hindi]]\n| location             = [[Mumbai]]\n| network              = [[Zee TV]]\n| first_aired          = {{start date|2006|09|26}}\n| last_aired           = {{end date|2009|08|27}}\n| num_seasons          = 1\n| num_episodes         = 595\n| website              = http://www.zeetv.com/shows/ghar-ki-lakshmi-betiyann.html\n}}\n\n'''''Ghar Ki Lakshmi Betiyann''''' (The wealth of the house - daughters) (also known as '''''Betiyann''''') (International Title:'''''Destiny''''') is a Hindi language television drama-series that aired on [[Zee TV]]. It premiered on 26 September 2006 and was directed by director, Rajan Shahi.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2006/20060927/delhi.htm#11|title=New soap opera goes on air|publisher=Tribune India|date=2006-09-27}}</ref> The serial ended on 27 August 2009. This serial was produced under the banner of Creative Eye Ltd. Please  belong it back  to zee world\n\n==Other versions/telecasts==\nAn [[Arabic]] dubbed-version premiered on [[Zee Alwan]] under the name \"Al Banat Zinat Al Bayt\" - girls are the beauty of the house/\"\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a \u0632\u064a\u0646\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u064a\u062a\", the second season aired on 16 April 2014.\n\nThe Show was dubbed In English and aired on [[Zee World]] on [[DStv|DSTv]] channel number 166.\n\nThe Show was dubbed In French and aired on [[Zee Magic]] on [[Canal Sat]] channel number 51.\n\nThe Show was dubbed In Indonesian and aired on [[Zee Bioskop]] on [[MNC Vision]] channel number 23.\n\n==Summary==\nSuryakant Gadodia is marries to Savitri and has four daughters - Saraswati, Gauri, Durga, and Lakshmi. He wants a son and marries Menaka, who gives birth to Yuvraj. Suryakant abandons his daughters and spoils Yuvraj, who grows up insolent and arrogant.\n\nMenaka wishes to have sole rights to the household and wants to get the daughters married as soon as possible. She arranges Bhavishya Kapadia, an abusive man, to marry Saraswati. Her lover Kshitij saves her when her husband tries to set her alive, and after a long trial, the sisters win the case. Saraswati becomes pregnant after Bhavishya is imprisoned, and then marries Kshitij.\n\nThe youngest, lively Lakshmi is to wed Satyakam, who also helps find clues against Kapadia, but he dies, leaving her in a state of shock. She later meets Karan, who has come to the Gadodias to avenge his mother, who was actually harassed by Menaka's brother. He then marries Lakshmi, and in the end,  finds out she is pregnant.\n\nYuvraj is trapped by a prostitute Kajri, who he disguises as a traditional woman Pavitra, and marries. He is greedy and rebukes his mother. The sisters find his secret out, and Suryakant disowns Yuvraj.\n\nAs the show ends, Gauri is married to Akash Shah, and Durga marries Bhavishya's lookalike Ranbir Dhawaan, and Saraswati reluctantly accepts the alliance.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Rohini Hattangadi]] / Nayan Bhatt as Gayatri Garodia (Baa)\n* [[Yatin Karyekar]] as Suryakant Garodia \n* Aishwarya Narkar as Savitri Suryakant Garodia\n* Tanushree Kaushal as Menka Garodia\n* Vikrant Rai / Hemant Thatte as Kshitij Gandhi \n* [[Kshitee Jog]] as Saraswati Garodia / Saraswati Bhavishya Kapadia / Saraswati Kshitij Gandhi \n* [[Neetha Shetty]] / [[Aleeza Khan]] as Gauri Garodia / Gauri Akash Shah \n* Smriti Mohan as Durga Garodia / Durga Ranveer Dhawan \n* [[Twinkle Bajpai]] / [[Gunjan Walia]] as Lakshmi Garodia / Lakshmi Karan Mathur \n* [[Romit Raj]] as Yuvraj Garodia \n* Yuvraj Mehra as Puneet Gandhi\n* Yuvraj Malhotra as Karan Mathur\n* [[Manini Mishra]] as Chanchal\n* Kartik Sabharwal as Bhavishya Kapadia / Ranveer Dhawan\n* [[Shishir Sharma]] / Sai Ballal as Nekchand Kapadia\n* Natasha Rana as Dhara Nekchand Kapadia\n* [[Sid Makkar]] as Satyakam Kapadia\n* [[Chhavi Mittal]] as Preeti \n* [[Jasveer Kaur]] as Kajri Bai / Pavitra Yuvraj Garodia\n* [[Gulfam Khan]] as Rasili Bai \n* Nupur Alankar as Halki Bhen \n* Suchitra Bandrekar as Phulki Garodia\n* Shekhar Shukla as Hasmukh Bhai\n* [[Rajendra Chawla]] as Rasik Bhai\n* [[Amit Dolawat]] as Prince / Dev \n* Niyati Joshi as Niyati Yuvraj Garodia\n* [[Narayani Shastri]] as Advocate Damini Verma\n* [[Gaurav Chopra]] as Advocate Kapil Singhania\n* Alka Ashlesha as Mrs. Verma (Damini's Mother)\n* [[Soni Singh]] as Jhumki Rani / Janvi Garodia / Janvi Nikhil Singhania \n* [[Yash Pandit]] as Prakash\n* Karan Hukku as Nikhil Singhania\n* Jatin Shah as Akash Shah\n* Mahru Sheikh as Devyani Shah\n* [[Nimai Bali]] as Suraj Pratap Singh\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Zee TV Programmes}}\n\n[[Category:2000s Indian television series]]\n[[Category:2006 Indian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2009 Indian television series endings]]\n[[Category:Indian television soap operas]]\n[[Category:Zee TV television series]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Ban ti pitin ki mank rol\n| image                = Betiyaan.jpg\n| caption              =\n| picture_format       = [[576i]]\n| runtime              = approximately 23 minutes\n| creator              = [[Creative Eye Limited]]\n| director             = Rajan Shahi<br>Romesh Kalra<br>Sunand Kumar Baranwal<br>\n                         Santosh Bhatt\n| producer             = {{ubl|Dheeraj Kumar|Zuby Kochhar}}\n| company              = [[Creative Eye Limited]]\n| starring             = [[Kshitee Jog]] <br> [[Aleeza Khan]] <br> Smriti Mohan <br> [[Gunjan Walia]] <br> [[Soni Singh]]                             \n| opentheme            = \"Ghar Ki Lakshmi Betiyann\" \n| country              = India\n| language             = [[Hindi]]\n| location             = [[Mumbai]]\n| network              = [[Zee TV]]\n| first_aired          = {{start date|2006|09|26}}\n| last_aired           = {{end date|2009|08|27}}\n| num_seasons          = 1\n| num_episodes         = 595\n| website              = http://www.zeetv.com/shows/ghar-ki-lakshmi-betiyann.html\n}}\n\n'''''Ghar Ki Lakshmi Betiyann''''' (The wealth of the house - daughters) (also known as '''''Betiyann''''') (International Title:'''''Destiny''''') is a Hindi language television drama-series that aired on [[Zee TV]]. It premiered on 26 September 2006 and was directed by director, Rajan Shahi.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2006/20060927/delhi.htm#11|title=New soap opera goes on air|publisher=Tribune India|date=2006-09-27}}</ref> The serial ended on 27 August 2009. This serial was produced under the banner of Creative Eye Ltd.\n\n==Other versions/telecasts==\nAn [[Arabic]] dubbed-version premiered on [[Zee Alwan]] under the name \"Al Banat Zinat Al Bayt\" - girls are the beauty of the house/\"\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a \u0632\u064a\u0646\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u064a\u062a\", the second season aired on 16 April 2014.\n\nThe Show was dubbed In English and aired on [[Zee World]] on [[DStv|DSTv]] channel number 166.\n\nThe Show was dubbed In French and aired on [[Zee Magic]] on [[Canal Sat]] channel number 51.\n\nThe Show was dubbed In Indonesian and aired on [[Zee Bioskop]] on [[MNC Vision]] channel number 23.\n\n==Summary==\nSuryakant Gadodia is marries to Savitri and has four daughters - Saraswati, Gauri, Durga, and Lakshmi. He wants a son and marries Menaka, who gives birth to Yuvraj. Suryakant abandons his daughters and spoils Yuvraj, who grows up insolent and arrogant.\n\nMenaka wishes to have sole rights to the household and wants to get the daughters married as soon as possible. She arranges Bhavishya Kapadia, an abusive man, to marry Saraswati. Her lover Kshitij saves her when her husband tries to set her alive, and after a long trial, the sisters win the case. Saraswati becomes pregnant after Bhavishya is imprisoned, and then marries Kshitij.\n\nThe youngest, lively Lakshmi is to wed Satyakam, who also helps find clues against Kapadia, but he dies, leaving her in a state of shock. She later meets Karan, who has come to the Gadodias to avenge his mother, who was actually harassed by Menaka's brother. He then marries Lakshmi, and in the end,  finds out she is pregnant.\n\nYuvraj is trapped by a prostitute Kajri, who he disguises as a traditional woman Pavitra, and marries. He is greedy and rebukes his mother. The sisters find his secret out, and Suryakant disowns Yuvraj.\n\nAs the show ends, Gauri is married to Akash Shah, and Durga marries Bhavishya's lookalike Ranbir Dhawaan, and Saraswati reluctantly accepts the alliance.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Rohini Hattangadi]] / Nayan Bhatt as Gayatri Garodia (Baa)\n* [[Yatin Karyekar]] as Suryakant Garodia \n* Aishwarya Narkar as Savitri Suryakant Garodia\n* Tanushree Kaushal as Menka Garodia\n* Vikrant Rai / Hemant Thatte as Kshitij Gandhi \n* [[Kshitee Jog]] as Saraswati Garodia / Saraswati Bhavishya Kapadia / Saraswati Kshitij Gandhi \n* [[Neetha Shetty]] / [[Aleeza Khan]] as Gauri Garodia / Gauri Akash Shah \n* Smriti Mohan as Durga Garodia / Durga Ranveer Dhawan \n* [[Twinkle Bajpai]] / [[Gunjan Walia]] as Lakshmi Garodia / Lakshmi Karan Mathur \n* [[Romit Raj]] as Yuvraj Garodia \n* Yuvraj Mehra as Puneet Gandhi\n* Yuvraj Malhotra as Karan Mathur\n* [[Manini Mishra]] as Chanchal\n* Kartik Sabharwal as Bhavishya Kapadia / Ranveer Dhawan\n* [[Shishir Sharma]] / Sai Ballal as Nekchand Kapadia\n* Natasha Rana as Dhara Nekchand Kapadia\n* [[Sid Makkar]] as Satyakam Kapadia\n* [[Chhavi Mittal]] as Preeti \n* [[Jasveer Kaur]] as Kajri Bai / Pavitra Yuvraj Garodia\n* [[Gulfam Khan]] as Rasili Bai \n* Nupur Alankar as Halki Bhen \n* Suchitra Bandrekar as Phulki Garodia\n* Shekhar Shukla as Hasmukh Bhai\n* [[Rajendra Chawla]] as Rasik Bhai\n* [[Amit Dolawat]] as Prince / Dev \n* Niyati Joshi as Niyati Yuvraj Garodia\n* [[Narayani Shastri]] as Advocate Damini Verma\n* [[Gaurav Chopra]] as Advocate Kapil Singhania\n* Alka Ashlesha as Mrs. Verma (Damini's Mother)\n* [[Soni Singh]] as Jhumki Rani / Janvi Garodia / Janvi Nikhil Singhania \n* [[Yash Pandit]] as Prakash\n* Karan Hukku as Nikhil Singhania\n* Jatin Shah as Akash Shah\n* Mahru Sheikh as Devyani Shah\n* [[Nimai Bali]] as Suraj Pratap Singh\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Zee TV Programmes}}\n\n[[Category:2000s Indian television series]]\n[[Category:2006 Indian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2009 Indian television series endings]]\n[[Category:Indian television soap operas]]\n[[Category:Zee TV television series]]\n", "name_user": "41.13.82.61", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghar_Ki_Lakshmi_Betiyann"}
{"title_page": "Bangladesh Railway", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Bangladesh Railway\n| native_name         = {{lang|bn|\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7}}\n| logo                = \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7.jpg\n| logo_size           = \n| type                = Department of the [[Government of Bangladesh]]\n| industry            = Railway\n| foundation          = 1862\n| dissolved           = \n| location_city       = Dhaka\n| locations           = <!--# of locations-->\n| area_served         = Bangladesh\n| key_people          = Mohammad Amzad Hossain, Director General of Bangladesh Railway<ref>{{cite web|url=http://railway.portal.gov.bd/site/page/cc819e84d-0071-4411-b6b9-cbd30bd6fdc |title=&#124; Bangladesh Railway-Government of the People of Republic Bangladesh &#124; \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7-\u0997\u09a3\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09c0 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0 |publisher=Railway.portal.gov.bd |accessdate=2016-08-06}}</ref>\n| products            = \n| services            = \n| revenue             = {{lang|bn|[[Bangladeshi taka|\u09f3]]}} 8,002 million<ref name=\"adb.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.adb.org/sites/default/files/linked-documents/49094-001-sd-01.pdf |title=Railway Reform Progress Report |website=Adb.org |accessdate=2016-08-07}}</ref>\n| revenue_year        = 2014\n| operating_income    = \n| net_income          = {{loss}} {{lang|bn|[[Bangladeshi taka|\u09f3]]}} - 8,015 million<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n| net_income_year     = 2014\n| aum                 = Rail Transport\n| num_employees       = 27,535<ref name=\"personnel\">[http://railway.portal.gov.bd/site/page/5c72f07e-c25d-4d3d-89bd-adc04ed4dbc4/\u099c\u09a8\u09ac\u09b2] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602225053/http://railway.portal.gov.bd/site/page/5c72f07e-c25d-4d3d-89bd-adc04ed4dbc4/ |date=2 June 2016 }}</ref>\n| num_employees_year  = 2015\n| owner               = [[British Raj]] {{small|(Until 1947)}}<br />[[Dominion of Pakistan]] {{small|(1947-1956)}}<br />[[Government of Pakistan]] {{small|(1956-1962)}}<br />[[Government of East Pakistan]] {{small|(1962-1971)}}<br />[[Government of Bangladesh]] {{small|(1971-Present)}}\n| parent              = [[Government of Bangladesh]]\n| divisions           = [[East Zone (Bangladesh Railway)|East Zone]] and [[West Zone (Bangladesh Railway)|West Zone]]\n| subsid              = \n| footnotes           = \n| location_country    = Bangladesh\n| homepage            = {{url|http://www.railway.gov.bd/}}\n| nobridges           = 3,650 <ref name=\"adb.org\"/> <br>\nMajor = 546<br>\nMinor = 3,104\n| ridership           = 65 million<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n| passkm              = 8,135 million<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n| nostations          = 454\n| length              = 2,885 km<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n| longestbridge       = [[Bangabandhu Bridge]]\n| doublelength        = 364 km<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n| intl                = Yes\n| gauge2              = [[Broad-gauge]]\n| gauge1length        = 1,838 km<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n| gauge1              = <nowiki>[[Meter-gauge]</nowiki>\n| freight             = 2.52 million tonnes<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n| gauge2length        = 682 km<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n}}\n{{Infobox rail network\n|name            = Bangla Rail\n|color           = \n|logo            = \n|image           = \n|caption         = \n|nationalrailway = [[Ministry of Railways (Bangladesh)|Ministry of Railways]]\n|infrastructure  = \n|majoroperators  = Bangladesh Railway\n|ridership       = 65 million (2014) <ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n|passkm          = 8,135 million<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n|freight         = 2.52 million tonnes<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n|length          = 2,885 km<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n|doublelength    = 364 km<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n|ellength        = \n|freightlength   = \n|hslength        = \n|ogauge          = \n|ogaugelength    = \n|gauge           = \n|hsgauge         = \n|gauge1          = Metre gauge\n|gauge1length    = 1,838 km<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n|gauge2          = Broad gauge\n|gauge2length    = 682 km<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n|gauge3          = \n|gauge3length    = \n|gauge4          = \n|gauge4length    = \n|el              = \n|el1             = \n|el1length       = \n|el2             = \n|el2length       = \n|el3             = \n|el3length       = \n|notunnels       = \n|tunnellength    = \n|longesttunnel   = \n|nobridges       = 3,650<ref name=\"adb.org\"/> <br> 546 (Major) <br> 3,104 (Minor)\n|longestbridge   = [[Bangabandhu Bridge]] (dual gauge, 4.8 km)<br>[[Hardinge Bridge]] (broad gauge, 1.8 km)\n|nostations      = 498\n|highelevation   = \n|highelat        = \n|lowelevation    = \n|lowelat         = \n|map             = \n|mapcaption      = \n}}\n\n'''Bangladesh Railway''' ({{lang-bn|\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7}}) also known as '''Bangla Rail''' is the state-owned rail transport agency of [[Bangladesh]]. It operates and maintains all railways in the country, and is overseen by the Directorate General of Bangladesh Railway. The Bangladesh Railway is governed by the [[Ministry of Railways (Bangladesh)|Ministry of Railways]] and the Bangladesh Railway Authority. Its [[reporting mark]] is \"BR\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mor.gov.bd/site/page/4392da01-5ee6-42b8-b03f-d4028daf0751/History-and-main-activities|title=\u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u09aa\u09a5 \u09ae\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09a3\u09be\u09b2\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b8\u0982\u0995\u09cd\u09b7\u09bf\u09aa\u09cd\u09a4 \u0987\u09a4\u09bf\u09b9\u09be\u09b8 \u0993 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a7\u09be\u09a8 \u0995\u09be\u09b0\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09ac\u09b2\u09c0 {{!}}Ministry of Railways-Government of the People's Republic of Bangladesh {{!}} \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u09aa\u09a5 \u09ae\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09a3\u09be\u09b2\u09af\u09bc-\u0997\u09a3\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09c0 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0|website=www.mor.gov.bd|access-date=2017-08-17}}</ref>\n\nThe Bangladesh Railway system has a total length of 2,855 route km. In 2009, Bangladesh Railway had 34,168 employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railway.gov.bd/br_short.asp|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091203022024/http://www.railway.gov.bd/br_short.asp|archivedate=3 December 2009|url-status=dead|accessdate=2009-12-15|df=dmy}}</ref> In 2014, Bangladesh Railway carried 65 million passengers and 2.52 million tonnes of freight. The railway made 8,135 million passenger-kilometres and 677 million tonne-kilometres.<ref name=\"adb.org\" />\n\n==History==\n\nRail transport in Bangladesh began on 15 November 1862, when 53.11&nbsp;km of {{RailGauge|5ft6in}} ([[5 ft 6 in gauge railway|broad gauge]]) line was opened between [[Darshana railway station|Darshana]] in [[Chuadanga District]] and Jogotee in [[Kushtia District]]. On 4 January 1885, a further 14.98&nbsp;km {{RailGauge|1000mm}} ([[Metre gauge railway|metre gauge]]) line was opened. In 1891, the [[Bengal Assam Railway]] was constructed with the assistance of the government. It was later run by the Bengal Assam Railway Company.\n\nOn 1 July 1895, two sections of metre gauge railway were constructed by English railway companies. One connected [[Chittagong]] and [[Comilla]] (149.89&nbsp;km). The other connected [[Laksam Upazila]] and [[Chandpur, Bangladesh|Chandpur]] (50.89&nbsp;km).<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=http://www.railway.gov.bd/history.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-02-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071115201005/http://www.railway.gov.bd/history.asp |archivedate=15 November 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn 1947, at the time of the [[Partition of India]], the Bengal Assam Railway was divided into two parts. The 2,603.92&nbsp;km of track located in [[East Pakistan]], came under the control of the central [[Government of Pakistan]]. On 1 February 1961, the Eastern Bengal Railway was renamed the \"[[Pakistan Eastern Railway]]\". In 1962, control of the Pakistan Eastern Railway was transferred to the [[Government of East Pakistan]]. On 9 June 1962, by order of the president, the Pakistan Eastern Railway management was assumed by a Railway Board.<ref name=history />\n\nIn 2005, the total length of the Bangladesh Railway was 2,855&nbsp;km.<ref name=\"len\">{{cite web|url=http://www.railway.gov.bd/Faq.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2005-12-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051220011537/http://www.railway.gov.bd/Faq.html |archivedate=20 December 2005 |df=dmy }}</ref> There was 660&nbsp;km of broad gauge track (mostly in the western region), 1,830&nbsp;km of metre gauge track (mostly in the central and eastern regions) and 365&nbsp;km of [[dual gauge]] track.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railway.gov.bd/track_bridges_stations.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091231055149/http://www.railway.gov.bd/track_bridges_stations.asp |archivedate=31 December 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> In 1998, the [[Jamuna Bridge]] was built to connect the previously divided east and west rail networks in dual gauge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railway.gov.bd/site/page/ff534cd8-a522-4c7d-a48c-6d41dc63aa82/%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%93%E0%A7%9F%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%81%E0%A6%9F-%E0%A6%AE%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%AA|title=Railway Route Map -Bangladesh Railway-Government of the People of Republic Bangladesh - \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7-\u0997\u09a3\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09c0 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0|accessdate=6 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, funding was received for a bridge over the [[Titas River]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railway-technology.com/news/news91253.html?WT.mc_id=DN_News|title=Bangladesh and India Finalise Rail Projects|website=Railway Technology|access-date=20 March 2016|date=22 July 2010}}</ref> In September 2010, the Government of Bangladesh approved ten rail development projects costing 19\u00b79 billion [[Bangladeshi taka]] including plans for new tracks and [[rolling stock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/development-projects-get-the-go-ahead.html\n| accessdate=28 September 2010 |title=Railway Gazette: Development projects get the go-ahead\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100929235952/http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/development-projects-get-the-go-ahead.html| archivedate= 29 September 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, [[Sheikh Hasina|Sheikh Hasina Wazed]], the Prime Minister of Bangladesh, officiated at the start of construction of a link which would cross several rivers to reach [[Cox's Bazar]]. The 100&nbsp;km of gauge line started from the [[railhead]] at [[Dohazari]], southeast of Chittagong. The plan was to reach Satkania, Dulahazra, Chakarin, Edgaon, Ramu and Cox's Bazar, with four major river bridges and a 28&nbsp;km branch from Ramu to Gundum. In 2013, the [[Chittagong Circular Railway]] was completed.\n\nIn 2015, construction of a 15&nbsp;km branch to [[Agartala]], [[Tripura]] in [[Northeast India]] commenced.<ref>{{cite news|title=Work on new India-Bangladesh railway link from 2015|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Work-on-new-India-Bangladesh-railway-link-from-2015/articleshow/36725087.cms|accessdate=7 December 2014|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=Jun 17, 2014}}</ref> In 2017, land acquisition took place to facilitate the construction.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/rail-project-to-connect-india-and-bangladesh-begins-land-acquisition-notices-served-to-257-families-3873163.html|title=Rail project to connect India and Bangladesh begins; land acquisition notices served to 257 families|date=2017-07-30|work=Firstpost|access-date=2017-08-17}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nFrom the end of the [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] in 1971 until 1982, the railway was governed by a Railway Board. It then came under the Railway Division of the Ministry of Communications. The Director General of the railway was the Secretary of the Railway Division of the Ministry of Communications. In 1995, governance of the railway was assumed by the \"Bangladesh Railway Authority\" which was chaired by the Minister of Railways.<ref name=\"brorg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mor.gov.bd/ |title=Ministry of Railways-Government of the People's Republic of Bangladesh &#124; \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u09aa\u09a5 \u09ae\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09a3\u09be\u09b2\u09af\u09bc-\u0997\u09a3\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09c0 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0 |website=Mor.gov.bd |date=2016-02-28 |accessdate=2016-08-07}}</ref> Inspections are made by an external government authority.\n\nThe features of Bangladesh Railway include the usage of several gauges and the division of the rail system by the [[Jamuna River (Bangladesh)|Jamuna River]], Brahmaputra into the Western Zone and the Eastern Zone of operations. Crossing the river is one bridge, the Jamuna Bridge which was completed in 2003.\n\nThe East Zone and the West Zone each have a General Manager who answers to the Director General of the Railway Authority. Each zone has its own raft of departments for operation, maintenance, and finances. Each zone is divided into two divisions with departments for personnel, transportation, commercial, finance mechanical, way and works signalling, telecommunication, electrical and medical services.\n\nThe East Zone has a workshop division in [[Pahartali Thana|Pahartali]]. The West Zone's workshop division is in [[Saidpur, Rajshahi Division|Saidpur]]. The railway has a central locomotive workshop for broad and metre gauge locomotives in [[Parbatipur Upazila|Parbatipur]]. It also has a Railway Training Academy.<ref name=brorg/> There is are diesel workshops in Pahartali, Dhaka and Parbatipur. Maintenance on coaches and wagons is carried out at the \"C and W\" shop in Saidpur, [[Nilphamari]] and at the \"C and W\" shop Pahartali.\n\n==Rolling stock==\n===Locomotives===\n{{main|Locomotives of Bangladesh}}\n\n====Diesel====\n[[File:BR 2934.jpg|thumb|[[Bangladesh Railway Class 2900]] locomotive]]\nBangladesh Railway's fleet of [[diesel locomotive]]s includes both diesel-electric and diesel-hydraulic machines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railway.gov.bd/rolling_stock.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-09-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830132319/http://www.railway.gov.bd/rolling_stock.asp |archivedate=30 August 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> In 2007, there were 77 broad gauge diesel-electric locomotives. In 2012, Bangladesh Railway ordered 16 new broad gauge locomotives of 3100&nbsp;hp from [[Diesel Locomotive Works]], India.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.globalrailnews.com/2012/08/28/dlw-bags-order-for-16-locomotives-from-bangladesh-railways/|title = DLW bags order for 16 locomotives from Bangladesh Railways|date = 28 August 2012|access-date = 28 August 2017|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170828062624/https://www.globalrailnews.com/2012/08/28/dlw-bags-order-for-16-locomotives-from-bangladesh-railways/|archive-date = 28 August 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref> There were also 208 metre gauge diesel-electric locomotives including those of classes [[Bangladesh Railway Class 2000|2000]], [[Bangladesh Railway Class 2600|2600]], [[Bangladesh Railway Class 2700|2700]], and [[Bangladesh Railway Class 2900|2900]]. The total number was 285.\n\nIn 2019, 40 EMD GT42ACLs were ordered from [[Progress Rail Services]].<ref>[https://www.railwayage.com/mechanical/locomotives/bangladesh-taps-progress-rail-for-gt-series-power/?RAchannel=news Bangladesh taps Progress Rail for GT Series power] ''[[Railway Age]]'' 2 July 2019</ref>\n\n====Steam====\nA small number of [[steam locomotive]]s are preserved in Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.internationalsteam.co.uk/trains/bangladesh01.htm |title=Preserved Steam Locomotives in Bangladesh |publisher=Internationalsteam.co.uk |accessdate=2016-08-06}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Location\n! Builder\n! Wheel<br />arrangement\n! Gauge\n|-\n| Dhaka Railway HQ\n| [[Nippon Sharyo|Nippon]]\n| [[2-8-2]]\n| Metre gauge\n|-\n| Saidpur Works\n| [[W. G. Bagnall]]\n| [[2-4-0]]T\n| {{RailGauge|2ft 6in}}\n|-\n| Saidpur Works\n| [[Vulcan Foundry]]\n| [[0-6-0]]\n| {{RailGauge|5ft 6in}}\n|-\n| Paksey Railway HQ\n| Vulcan Foundry?\n| [[2-4-0]]T\n| {{RailGauge|2ft 6in}}\n|}\n\nThe 762&nbsp;mm gauge locomotives are from the Rupsa {{ndash}} [[Bagerhat District|Bagerhat]] railway which was the only 762&nbsp;mm gauge line in East Pakistan in 1947. It was changed to 1,676&nbsp;mm gauge in 1970.\n\n=== Diesel-electric Multiple Unit ===\n[[File:Bangladesh Railway, Komlapur Railway Station.jpg|thumb|A DEMU train at Kamalapur Railway Station, Dhaka]]\nDiesel-electric Multiple Unit (DEMU) trains first started their journey in Bangladesh with the introduction of Dhaka-Narayangonj Commuter train on 24th April, 2013<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bangla.bdnews24.com/economy/article1644488.bdnews|title=\u099a\u09c0\u09a8\u09be \u09a1\u09c7\u09ae\u09c1 \u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a8 \u0986\u09b0 \u0995\u09bf\u09a8\u09ac\u09c7 \u09a8\u09be \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0|last=\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a4\u09bf\u09ac\u09c7\u09a6\u0995|first=\u099c\u09cd\u09af\u09c7\u09b7\u09cd\u09a0|last2=\u09a1\u099f\u0995\u09ae|first2=\u09ac\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09a8\u09bf\u0989\u099c \u099f\u09cb\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09a8\u09cd\u099f\u09bf\u09ab\u09cb\u09b0|website=bangla.bdnews24.com|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>. Total 20 sets of meter-gauge DEMU were manufactured by [[CRRC Tangshan|Tangshan Railway Vehicle Co Ltd]], China<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newagebd.net/article/78743/pm-opposes-import-of-demu-train|title=PM opposes import of DEMU train|website=New Age {{!}} The Most Popular Outspoken English Daily in Bangladesh|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>. Each set comprises of three units. Total 300 passengers can board a set, 149 by sitting and 151 by standing<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/302844/DEMU-train-becomes-burden-on-railway|title=DEMU train becomes burden on railway|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>. They are rated 460 hp and can run up to 20 km distance with a maximum speed of 80 km/h. They have a life-span of 30 years<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newagebd.net/article/78743/pm-opposes-import-of-demu-train|title=PM opposes import of DEMU train|website=New Age {{!}} The Most Popular Outspoken English Daily in Bangladesh|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>. Currently only 9 of 20 sets are active<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prothomalo.com/bangladesh/article/1443641|title=\u09a1\u09c7\u09ae\u09c1 \u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a8\u09c7\u09b0 \u099a\u09be\u09aa\u09c7 \u09ac\u09c7\u09b8\u09be\u09ae\u09be\u09b2 \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2|website=\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a5\u09ae \u0986\u09b2\u09cb|language=bn|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>.\n\n==Freight and cargo services==\nAs a national carrier, Bangladesh Railway is obliged to carry essential commodities such as grain and fertiliser to remote parts of Bangladesh at discounted rates. Bangladesh Railway transports containers from the [[Port of Chittagong]] to Dhaka Inland Container Depot, where there are [[customs]] facilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cpa.gov.bd/facilities-of-cpa/|title=Facilities of CPA \u2013 Chittagong Port Authority|website=cpa.gov.bd|access-date=20 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512173236/http://cpa.gov.bd/facilities-of-cpa/|archive-date=12 May 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> The rolling stock to carry containers was manufactured from existing stock. On 5 August 1991, a container-only train came into service. A goods train operates from [[Singhabad]] and [[Petrapole]], India to Rohanpur and [[Benapole]], Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://twocircles.net/2011sep21/india_approves_new_railway_link_bangladesh.html|title=India approves new railway link with Bangladesh |website=twocircles.net |access-date=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Accidents ===\n* On July 10, 2014, a major freight train accident occurred near [[Faujdarhat Railway Station]] at 6.30 am. A freight train from [[Patenga]] was carrying furnace oil to a power plant, but near Faujdarhat the train derailed and leaked around {{convert|21255|impgal|abbr=on}} of furnace oil. Six wagons of the train derailed and oil from three of the wagons flowed into a nearby canal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oil-laden train derails in Ctg|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/oil-laden-train-derails-in-ctg-32674|website=the daily star}}</ref>\n* On September 14, 2016, a freight train derailed in the [[Faujdarhat]] area. The loco driver and the assistant driver were injured.<ref>{{cite web|title=Home Bangladesh 2 injured in Ctg rail engine derailment|url=http://en.prothomalo.com/bangladesh/news/120877/2-injured-in-Ctg-rail-engine-derailment|website=prothom alo}}</ref>\n\n==Passenger services==\n[[File:Jamuna Express.jpg|thumb|Jamuna Express at Kamalapur station]]\n[[File:Parabat Express.jpg|thumb|Parabat Express at Sylhet station]] \nRailway is a principal mode of transport in Bangladesh. In the 2005 financial year, 42 million passengers travelled on the Bangladesh Railway.<ref name=stores>{{cite web|url=http://www.railway.gov.bd/stores.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091207001418/http://www.railway.gov.bd/stores.asp |archivedate=7 December 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> Inter-city services, contribute to over seventy percent of Bangladesh Railway's revenue.<ref name=stores /> In 2014, the railway owned 312 broad gauge coaches and 1,164 metre gauge coaches.<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n\nIn 2017, Bangladesh Railway operated 90 inter-city trains (up & down), 52 mail or express trains, 64 commuter trains ([[Diesel Multiple Unit|DEMU]]), 135 shuttle or local trains and 2 international services.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://railway.portal.gov.bd/site/page/e35cebe7-3b39-46be-ae6b-f267d4d1375f |script-title=bn:\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b0 \u09af\u09be\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09c0\u09ac\u09be\u09b9\u09c0 \u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a8|website=railway.portal.gov.bd |language=bn |access-date=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nTwo times per week, a passenger train operates a service to India. In April 2008, the [[Maitri Express]] between Dhaka and [[Kolkata]] came into operation on the Gede {{ndash}} Darsana route.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view//bangladesh-india-order-reopens.html | title=Bangladesh \u2013 India border reopens | work=[[Railway Gazette International]] | date=5 August 2007 }}</ref> On 9 November 2017, a new weekly train, the [[Bandhan Express]], came into operation between [[Khulna]] and Kolkata via Petrapole and Benapole (172&nbsp;km).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/pf_story.php?nid%3D50807 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-09-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518212137/http://www.thedailystar.net/pf_story.php?nid=50807 |archivedate=18 May 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nTickets for Bangladesh Railway services are available at all stations. Most stations are computerised and tickets which can be purchased within four days of departure, are printed. Full refunds (excluding clerical charges) are available up until two days before departure. The railway reserves ten percent of tickets for online sales. Of these tickets, fifteen percent are reserved for mobile phone sales.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://techthumbs.com/how-to-buy-bangladesh-railwaytrain-ticket-online|title=How to Buy Bangladesh Railway(Train) Ticket Online|date=2012-10-13|work=Tech Thumbs|access-date=2017-08-17}}</ref>\n\n===Accidents===\n* On 11 July 2006, a train collided with a crowded bus at an unmanned railroad crossing at [[Akkelpur Upazila]], Jaipurhat District. Thirty-three people died and thirty were injured.\n* On 13 October 2007, the rear carriages of the Probhati Express derailed near Dhaka. Four people died and fifty were injured.\n* On 16 April 2008, a Dinajpur {{ndash}} Dhaka Ekota express train collided with a local bus on a level crossing on the outskirts of Kalihati, [[Tangail District]]. Eighteen people died and thirty were injured.\n* On 14 May 2008, an Upaban express train crashed into the rear of a [[Noakhali]] express train at [[Ashuganj Upazila|the Ashuganj Upazila]] station, [[Brahmanbaria District]]. Eight people died and one hundred were injured.\n* On 8 December 2010, a collision between two passenger trains killed at least ten people.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.railwaysafrica.com/blog/2010/12/fatal-bangladesh-collision/ |title=Fatal Bangladesh Collision |date=12 December 2010 |website=Railways Africa |accessdate=12 December 2010}}</ref>\n* On 23 June 2019, several bogies of Dhaka-bound Upaban Express train from Sylhet veered off the tracks at around 11:40 pm after a culvert over the Barochhara Canal broke down, 200 yards off Baramchal Railway Station. At least five people died and hundreds were injured. Locals who worked overnight with the first responders claimed at least 10-15 people have been killed.<ref>{{cite web |date=24 June 2019 |title=Bangladesh: 5 killed as four train coaches derail, hundreds injured |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/world/story/bangladesh-5-killed-as-four-train-coaches-derail-hundreds-injured-1554855-2019-06-24 |work=India Today}}</ref>\n* On 12 November 2019, At least 16 passengers died and score other injured as Dhaka-bound Turna Nishita Express rammed Chattogram-bound Udayan Express from Sylhet at Mandobagh Railway Station in Kasba.[http://epaper.thedailystar.net/index.php?opt=view&page=1&date=2019-11-13 Train Driver's Fault' Takes Sixteen Lives]\n* On 14 November 2019, Two days after a deadly train crash in Brahmanbaria, Rangpur Express, bound from Dhaka to Rangpur, braced an accident at Ullapara station in Sirajganj at around 2pm on Thursday. Seven compartments of Rangpur Express, including its engine and power car, derailed in the Ullapara Railway Station area and a fire broke out in three of its compartments.\n\n===Accommodation classes===\nBangladesh Railway has three main passenger classes, \"Air conditioned\", \"First\" and \"Second\". Most trains do not provide the \"Air conditioned\" class. On inter-city and long-distance trains, a restaurant car and a power car are included at the centre of the train. All inter-city trains are partially air-conditioned, feature padded leather seats and provide passengers with on-demand sheets, pillows, blankets, as well as meals in a dining car. Some diesel{{ndash}}electric trains provider commuter services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://railway.portal.gov.bd/site/page/e35cebe7-3b39-46be-ae6b-f267d4d1375f/%25E0%25A6%25AF%25E0%25A6%25BE%25E0%25A6%25A4%25E0%25A7%258D%25E0%25A6%25B0%25E0%25A7%2580%25E0%25A6%25AC%25E0%25A6%25BE%25E0%25A6%25B9%25E0%25A7%2580-%25E0%25A6%259F%25E0%25A7%258D%25E0%25A6%25B0%25E0%25A7%2587%25E0%25A6%25A8|script-title=bn:\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b0 \u09af\u09be\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09c0\u09ac\u09be\u09b9\u09c0 \u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a8|website=railway.portal.gov.bd|language=bn|access-date=20 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324214752/http://railway.portal.gov.bd/site/page/e35cebe7-3b39-46be-ae6b-f267d4d1375f/%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%A4%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%80%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B9%E0%A7%80-%E0%A6%9F%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%A8|archive-date=24 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"border:1px solid black;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Class\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Description\n|-\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:20%;\"| '''Tapanukul ({{lang|bn|\u09a4\u09be\u09aa\u09be\u09a8\u09c1\u0995\u09c2\u09b2}})''' <br> '''First class AC'''\n| valign=\"top\" | This is the most expensive class. This air-conditioned coach is used only on popular Inter-City routes. The coaches are carpeted, have sleeping accommodation, ample leg room and have privacy features like personal coupes.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |'''First class ({{lang|bn|\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a5\u09ae \u09b6\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a3\u09c0}})'''\n| valign=\"top\" | This class is relatively luxurious, but not air-conditioned; has sleeping berths, and ample leg room.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''First class Chair<br> ({{lang|bn|\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a5\u09ae \u09b6\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a3\u09c0 \u099a\u09c7\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0}})'''\n| valign=\"top\" | Chair car or day coach with a total of five seats in a row on broad gauge trains and four seats in a row on metre gauge trains, used for daily travel.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''2nd Class-Shovon Chair<br> ({{lang|bn|\u09e8\u09af\u09bc \u09b6\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a3\u09c0-\u09b6\u09cb\u09ad\u09a8 \u099a\u09c7\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0}}) '''\n| valign=\"top\" | The 2nd Class Shovon Chair is basically a chair car preferred by most middle-class passengers. Has a total of five seats in a row on broad gauge trains and four seats in a row on metre gauge trains.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''2nd Class-Shovon<br> ({{lang|bn|\u09e8\u09af\u09bc \u09b6\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a3\u09c0-\u09b6\u09cb\u09ad\u09a8}}) '''\n| valign=\"top\" |  One of the cheapest classes; seats are not very comfortable.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''2nd Class-Shulov<br> ({{lang|bn|\u09e8\u09af\u09bc \u09b6\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a3\u09c0- \u09b8\u09c1\u09b2\u09ad}}) '''\n| valign=\"top\" | The cheapest accommodation, with seats made of pressed wood or steel and are cushioned. Only found in sub-urban and short-distance routes. Although entry into the compartment is guaranteed, a seat is not guaranteed. These coaches are usually very crowded.\n|}\n\n==List of railway stations in Bangladesh==\n[[Kamalapur Railway Station]] is the central railway station in Dhaka. In 2015, Bangladesh Railway serviced 489 railway stations. These include one block hut, thirteen train halts, and four goods booking points. The schedule of Bangladesh Railway has changed 26 Trains in the new year 2020. The East zone Train schedule will active on 10 January 2020<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bdteletalk.com/bangladesh-railway-schedule-time// |title=Bangladesh Railway Schedule, Time table |date=3 January 2020 |website=Bdteletalk.com |accessdate=3 January 2020}}</ref>.\n\nHere is a list of railway stations in Bangladesh district-wise:\n\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| image1 = Kamalapur Railway Station 4.jpg\n| caption1 = Kamalapur Railway Station\n| width1 = 200\n| image2 = Kamlan.jpg\n| caption2 = Kamalapur railway station at night\n| width2 = 200\n| image3 = \n| caption3 = Khulna railway station\n| width3 = 200\n| image4 = Rajshahi Railway Station 01.JPG\n| caption4 = Rajshahi railway station\n| width4 = 200\n| image5 = Sylhet Railway.jpg\n| caption5 = Sylhet Railway Station\n| width5 = 200\n| image6 = Parbatipur_Railway_Junction.JPG\n| caption6 = Parbatipur Railway Junction Station at Dinajpur District.\n| width6 = 200\n| image7 = Noapara.jpg\n| caption7 = Noapara Railway Station at Jessore District.\n| width7 = 200\n| width8 = 200\n| image9 = Tongi Railway Station, Bangladesh.JPG\n| caption9 = Tongi Railway Station, Dhaka\n| width9 = 200\n| image10 = Railway Airport.jpg\n| caption10 = Airport Railway Station\n| width10 = 200\n| total_width = \n| alt1 = \n}}\n\n=== Bogura ===\n\n# [[Santahar railway station|Santahar Junction Railway Station]]\n\n=== Brahmanbaria ===\n\n# Akhaura Junction Railway Station\n#Ashugonj Railway Station\n#Brahmanbaria Railway Station\n#Gangashagor Railway Station\n#Imambari Railway Station\n#Kosba Railway Station\n#Mondobag Railway Station\n#Paghachang Railway Station\n#Shaldandi Railway Station\n#Shashidol Railway Station\n#Talshohor Railway Station\n#Vatshala Railway Station\n\n=== Chandpur ===\n\n# Bolakhal Railway Station\n# [[Chandpur Railway Station]]\n# Chandpur Court Railway Station\n# Chitoshi Road Railway Station\n# Hajigonj Railway Station\n# Meher Railway Station\n# Modhu Road Railway Station\n# Moishadi Railway Station\n# Shahrasti Railway Station\n# Shahtoli Railway Station\n# Waruk Railway Station\n\n=== Chapai-Nobabgonj ===\n\n# [[Rohanpur railway station|Rohanpur Railway Station]]\n\n=== Chittagong ===\n\n# Barobokundo Railway Station\n# Baroiyadhala Railway Station\n# Bartakia Railway Station\n# Chinki Astana Railway Station\n# [[Chittagong]] Railway Station\n# Chittagong Junction Railway Station\n# Foujdarhat Railway Station\n# Kaibollo Dham Railway Station\n# Kumira Railway Station\n# Mastan Nagar Railway Station\n# Mirshorai Railway Station\n# Nijampur College Railway Station\n# Pahartoli Railway Station\n# Sitakundo Railway Station\n# Vatiari Railway Station\n\n=== Chuadanga ===\n\n#[[Alamdanga Railway Station]]\n#[[Chuadanga railway station|Chuadanga Railway Station]]\n#[[Darshana railway station|Darshana Halt Railway Station]]\n\n=== Comilla ===\n\n#Alisshor Railway Station\n#Bipulashar Railway Station\n#Comilla Railway Station\n#Doulotgonj Railway Station\n#Gunboti Railway Station\n# Hasanpur Railway Station\n#Khila Railway Station\n# [[Laksam Railway Junction|Laksam Junction Railway Station]]\n#Lalmai Railway Station\n#Moynamati Railway Station\n# Nangol Coat Railway Station\n# Naoti Railway Station\n#Nather Petua Railway Station\n#Rajapur Railway Station\n#Sadar Rosulpur Railway Station\n\n=== Dhaka ===\n\n#[[Airport railway station, Dhaka|Airport Railway Station]]\n#Banani Railway Station\n#[[Dhaka Cantonment|Dhaka Cantonment Railway Station]]\n#[[Kamalapur railway station|Kamalapur Railway Station]]\n#Tejgaon Railway Station\n\n=== Dinajpur ===\n\n#[[Birampur railway station|Birampur Railway Station]]\n#[[Dinajpur railway station|Dinajpur Railway Station]]\n#[[Hili railway station|Hili Railway Station]]\n#[[Parbatipur railway station|Parbatipur Railway Station]]\n\n=== Faridpur ===\n\n# [[Faridpur, Bangladesh|Faridpur Railway Station]]\n\n=== Feni ===\n\n# Belunia Railway Station\n# Fazilpur Railway Station\n# Feni Junction Railway Station\n# Kalidoho Railway Station\n# Muhurigonj Railway Station\n# Sharshadi Railway Station\n\n=== Gazipur ===\n\n# Arikhola Railway Station\n#Pubail Railway Station\n#Nolchata Railway Station\n#[[Joydebpur railway station|Joydebpur Railway Station]]\n#Tongi Junction Railway Station\n\n=== Habigonj ===\n\n# Shaistaganj Railway Station\n\n=== Jamalpur ===\n\n# [[Dewangonj]] Bazar Railway Station\n\n=== Jessore ===\n\n# [[Jessore railway station|Jessore Railway Station]]\n\n=== Joypurhat ===\n\n#[[Akkelpur railway Station|Akkelpur Railway Station]]\n#[[Jafarpur railway station|Jafarpur Railway Station]]\n#[[Jamalganj railway station|Jamalganj Railway Station]]\n#[[Joypurhat railway station|Joypurhat Railway Station]]\n#[[Panchbibi railway station|Panchbibi Railway Station]]\n\n=== Kishorgonj ===\n\n# Bhairab Bazar Junction Railway Station\n\n=== Khulna ===\n\n# [[Khulna railway station|Khulna Railway Station]]\n\n=== Kushtia ===\n\n# [[Bheramara railway station|Bheramara Railway Station]]\n# [[Poradoho Jn|Poradoho Junction Railway Station]]\n\n=== Lalmonirhat ===\n\n# [[Lalmonirhat railway station|Lalmonirhat Railway Station]]\n#[[Burimari railway station|Burimari Railway Station]]\n\n=== Moulovi Bazar ===\n\n# Boromchal Railway Station\n#Chokapon Railway Station\n#[[Kulaura|Kulaura Junction Railway Station]]\n\n=== Mymenshingh ===\n\n# Mymensingh Junction Railway Station\n#[[Gouripur, Bangladesh|Gouripur Junction Railway Station]]\n\n=== Naogaon ===\n\n# [[Ahsanganj railway station|Ahsanganj Railway Station]]\n\n=== Narshingdi ===\n\n# Amirgonj Railway Station\n# Doulatkandi Railway Station\n# Ghorashal Railway Station\n# Ghorashal Flag Railway Station\n# Jinarodi Railway Station\n# Hatuvanga Railway Station\n# Khanabari Railway Station\n# Methikanda Railway Station\n# Narshingdi Railway Station\n# Shrinidhi Railway Station\n\n=== Natore ===\n\n# [[Abdulpur railway station|Abdulpur Railway Station]]\n\n=== Netrokona ===\n\n# [[Mohonganj]] Railway Station\n\n=== Nilphamari ===\n\n# Syedpur Railway Station\n#[[Chilahati railway station|Chilahati Railway Station]]\n\n=== Noakhali ===\n\n# Bozra Railway Station\n# Choumuhoni Railway Station\n# Harinarayanpur Railway Station\n# Maizdi Railway Station\n# Maizdi Court Railway Station\n# Noakhali Railway Station\n# Shonaimuri Railway Station\n\n=== Pabna ===\n\n#[[Chatmohor railway station|Chatmohor Railway Station]]\n#[[Iswardi railway station|Iswardi Junction Railway Station]]\n#[[Ishwardi bypass|Ishwardi Bypass Railway Station]]\n#[[Pabna railway station|Pabna Railway Station]]\n\n=== Rajshahi ===\n\n# [[Rajshahi railway station|Rajshahi Railway Station]]\n\n=== Rangpur ===\n\n#[[Kaunia railway junction|Kaunia Railway Station]]\n#[[Rangpur railway station|Rangpur Railway Station]]\n\n=== Sirajgonj ===\n\n#[[Jamtoeel|Jamtoeel Railway Station]]\n#[[Sirajganj|Sirajganj Railway Station]], W, river port terminus of branch from [[Iswardi]], bypassed by Jamuna Bridge in 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adb.org/Documents/PERs/IN202_02.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-11-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090319111546/http://www.adb.org/Documents/PERs/IN202_02.pdf |archivedate=19 March 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n#[[Ullapara railway station|Ullapara Railway Station]]\n\n=== Sunamgonj ===\n\n# Chattakbazar Railway Station\n\n=== Sylhet ===\n\n# Fenchugonj Railway Station\n#Maizgaon Railway Station\n#Moglabazar Railway Station\n#[[Sylhet railway station|Sylhet Railway Station]]\n\n=== Tangail ===\n\n#[[Bongobondhu Shetu Purbo (East)|Bongobondhu Shetu Purbo Railway Station]]\n#[[Tangail railway station|Tangail Railway Station]]\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Transport in Bangladesh]]\n* [[Bandhan Express]]\n* [[Parabat Express]]\n* [[Kalni Express]]\n* [[Lalmoni Express]]\n* [[Dhaka\u2013Chittagong high-speed railway]]\n* [[Bangladesh Railway Museum]]\n* [[Railway Nirapatta Bahini]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.railway.gov.bd/ Official site, timetables]\n\n{{Asia in topic|Rail transport in}}\n{{Bangladesh topics}}\n{{Railways in Bangladesh}}\n{{Ministry of Railways (Bangladesh)}}\n\n[[Category:Bangladesh Railway| ]]\n[[Category:Railway companies of Bangladesh]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Bangladesh Railway\n| native_name         = {{lang|bn|\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7}}\n| logo                = \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7.jpg\n| logo_size           = \n| type                = Department of the [[Government of Bangladesh]]\n| industry            = Railway\n| foundation          = 1862\n| dissolved           = \n| location_city       = Dhaka\n| locations           = <!--# of locations-->\n| area_served         = Bangladesh\n| key_people          = Mohammad Amzad Hossain, Director General of Bangladesh Railway<ref>{{cite web|url=http://railway.portal.gov.bd/site/page/cc819e84d-0071-4411-b6b9-cbd30bd6fdc |title=&#124; Bangladesh Railway-Government of the People of Republic Bangladesh &#124; \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7-\u0997\u09a3\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09c0 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0 |publisher=Railway.portal.gov.bd |accessdate=2016-08-06}}</ref>\n| products            = \n| services            = \n| revenue             = {{lang|bn|[[Bangladeshi taka|\u09f3]]}} 8,002 million<ref name=\"adb.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.adb.org/sites/default/files/linked-documents/49094-001-sd-01.pdf |title=Railway Reform Progress Report |website=Adb.org |accessdate=2016-08-07}}</ref>\n| revenue_year        = 2014\n| operating_income    = \n| net_income          = {{loss}} {{lang|bn|[[Bangladeshi taka|\u09f3]]}} - 8,015 million<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n| net_income_year     = 2014\n| aum                 = Rail Transport\n| num_employees       = 27,535<ref name=\"personnel\">[http://railway.portal.gov.bd/site/page/5c72f07e-c25d-4d3d-89bd-adc04ed4dbc4/\u099c\u09a8\u09ac\u09b2] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602225053/http://railway.portal.gov.bd/site/page/5c72f07e-c25d-4d3d-89bd-adc04ed4dbc4/ |date=2 June 2016 }}</ref>\n| num_employees_year  = 2015\n| owner               = [[British Raj]] {{small|(Until 1947)}}<br />[[Dominion of Pakistan]] {{small|(1947-1956)}}<br />[[Government of Pakistan]] {{small|(1956-1962)}}<br />[[Government of East Pakistan]] {{small|(1962-1971)}}<br />[[Government of Bangladesh]] {{small|(1971-Present)}}\n| parent              = [[Government of Bangladesh]]\n| divisions           = [[East Zone (Bangladesh Railway)|East Zone]] and [[West Zone (Bangladesh Railway)|West Zone]]\n| subsid              = \n| footnotes           = \n| location_country    = Bangladesh\n| homepage            = {{url|http://www.railway.gov.bd/}}\n| nobridges           = 3,650 <ref name=\"adb.org\"/> <br>\nMajor = 546<br>\nMinor = 3,104\n| ridership           = 65 million<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n| passkm              = 8,135 million<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n| nostations          = 454\n| length              = 2,885 km<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n| longestbridge       = [[Bangabandhu Bridge]]\n| doublelength        = 364 km<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n| intl                = Yes\n| gauge2              = [[Broad-gauge]]\n| gauge1length        = 1,838 km<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n| gauge1              = <nowiki>[[Meter-gauge]</nowiki>\n| freight             = 2.52 million tonnes<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n| gauge2length        = 682 km<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n}}\n{{Infobox rail network\n|name            = Bangla Rail\n|color           = \n|logo            = \n|image           = \n|caption         = \n|nationalrailway = [[Ministry of Railways (Bangladesh)|Ministry of Railways]]\n|infrastructure  = \n|majoroperators  = Bangladesh Railway\n|ridership       = 65 million (2014) <ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n|passkm          = 8,135 million<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n|freight         = 2.52 million tonnes<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n|length          = 2,885 km<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n|doublelength    = 364 km<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n|ellength        = \n|freightlength   = \n|hslength        = \n|ogauge          = \n|ogaugelength    = \n|gauge           = \n|hsgauge         = \n|gauge1          = Metre gauge\n|gauge1length    = 1,838 km<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n|gauge2          = Broad gauge\n|gauge2length    = 682 km<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n|gauge3          = \n|gauge3length    = \n|gauge4          = \n|gauge4length    = \n|el              = \n|el1             = \n|el1length       = \n|el2             = \n|el2length       = \n|el3             = \n|el3length       = \n|notunnels       = \n|tunnellength    = \n|longesttunnel   = \n|nobridges       = 3,650<ref name=\"adb.org\"/> <br> 546 (Major) <br> 3,104 (Minor)\n|longestbridge   = [[Bangabandhu Bridge]] (dual gauge, 4.8 km)<br>[[Hardinge Bridge]] (broad gauge, 1.8 km)\n|nostations      = 498\n|highelevation   = \n|highelat        = \n|lowelevation    = \n|lowelat         = \n|map             = \n|mapcaption      = \n}}\n\n'''Bangladesh Railway''' ({{lang-bn|\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7}}) also known as '''Bangla Rail''' is the state-owned rail transport agency of [[Bangladesh]]. It operates and maintains all railways in the country, and is overseen by the Directorate General of Bangladesh Railway. The Bangladesh Railway is governed by the [[Ministry of Railways (Bangladesh)|Ministry of Railways]] and the Bangladesh Railway Authority. Its [[reporting mark]] is \"BR\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mor.gov.bd/site/page/4392da01-5ee6-42b8-b03f-d4028daf0751/History-and-main-activities|title=\u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u09aa\u09a5 \u09ae\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09a3\u09be\u09b2\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b8\u0982\u0995\u09cd\u09b7\u09bf\u09aa\u09cd\u09a4 \u0987\u09a4\u09bf\u09b9\u09be\u09b8 \u0993 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a7\u09be\u09a8 \u0995\u09be\u09b0\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09ac\u09b2\u09c0 {{!}}Ministry of Railways-Government of the People's Republic of Bangladesh {{!}} \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u09aa\u09a5 \u09ae\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09a3\u09be\u09b2\u09af\u09bc-\u0997\u09a3\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09c0 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0|website=www.mor.gov.bd|access-date=2017-08-17}}</ref>\n\nThe Bangladesh Railway system has a total length of 2,855 route km. In 2009, Bangladesh Railway had 34,168 employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railway.gov.bd/br_short.asp|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091203022024/http://www.railway.gov.bd/br_short.asp|archivedate=3 December 2009|url-status=dead|accessdate=2009-12-15|df=dmy}}</ref> In 2014, Bangladesh Railway carried 65 million passengers and 2.52 million tonnes of freight. The railway made 8,135 million passenger-kilometres and 677 million tonne-kilometres.<ref name=\"adb.org\" />\n\n==History==\n\nRail transport in Bangladesh began on 15 November 1862, when 53.11&nbsp;km of {{RailGauge|5ft6in}} ([[5 ft 6 in gauge railway|broad gauge]]) line was opened between [[Darshana railway station|Darshana]] in [[Chuadanga District]] and Jogotee in [[Kushtia District]]. On 4 January 1885, a further 14.98&nbsp;km {{RailGauge|1000mm}} ([[Metre gauge railway|metre gauge]]) line was opened. In 1891, the [[Bengal Assam Railway]] was constructed with the assistance of the government. It was later run by the Bengal Assam Railway Company.\n\nOn 1 July 1895, two sections of metre gauge railway were constructed by English railway companies. One connected [[Chittagong]] and [[Comilla]] (149.89&nbsp;km). The other connected [[Laksam Upazila]] and [[Chandpur, Bangladesh|Chandpur]] (50.89&nbsp;km).<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=http://www.railway.gov.bd/history.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-02-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071115201005/http://www.railway.gov.bd/history.asp |archivedate=15 November 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn 1947, at the time of the [[Partition of India]], the Bengal Assam Railway was divided into two parts. The 2,603.92&nbsp;km of track located in [[East Pakistan]], came under the control of the central [[Government of Pakistan]]. On 1 February 1961, the Eastern Bengal Railway was renamed the \"[[Pakistan Eastern Railway]]\". In 1962, control of the Pakistan Eastern Railway was transferred to the [[Government of East Pakistan]]. On 9 June 1962, by order of the president, the Pakistan Eastern Railway management was assumed by a Railway Board.<ref name=history />\n\nIn 2005, the total length of the Bangladesh Railway was 2,855&nbsp;km.<ref name=\"len\">{{cite web|url=http://www.railway.gov.bd/Faq.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2005-12-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051220011537/http://www.railway.gov.bd/Faq.html |archivedate=20 December 2005 |df=dmy }}</ref> There was 660&nbsp;km of broad gauge track (mostly in the western region), 1,830&nbsp;km of metre gauge track (mostly in the central and eastern regions) and 365&nbsp;km of [[dual gauge]] track.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railway.gov.bd/track_bridges_stations.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091231055149/http://www.railway.gov.bd/track_bridges_stations.asp |archivedate=31 December 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> In 1998, the [[Jamuna Bridge]] was built to connect the previously divided east and west rail networks in dual gauge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railway.gov.bd/site/page/ff534cd8-a522-4c7d-a48c-6d41dc63aa82/%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%93%E0%A7%9F%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%81%E0%A6%9F-%E0%A6%AE%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%AA|title=Railway Route Map -Bangladesh Railway-Government of the People of Republic Bangladesh - \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7-\u0997\u09a3\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09c0 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0|accessdate=6 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, funding was received for a bridge over the [[Titas River]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railway-technology.com/news/news91253.html?WT.mc_id=DN_News|title=Bangladesh and India Finalise Rail Projects|website=Railway Technology|access-date=20 March 2016|date=22 July 2010}}</ref> In September 2010, the Government of Bangladesh approved ten rail development projects costing 19\u00b79 billion [[Bangladeshi taka]] including plans for new tracks and [[rolling stock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/development-projects-get-the-go-ahead.html\n| accessdate=28 September 2010 |title=Railway Gazette: Development projects get the go-ahead\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100929235952/http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/development-projects-get-the-go-ahead.html| archivedate= 29 September 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, [[Sheikh Hasina|Sheikh Hasina Wazed]], the Prime Minister of Bangladesh, officiated at the start of construction of a link which would cross several rivers to reach [[Cox's Bazar]]. The 100&nbsp;km of gauge line started from the [[railhead]] at [[Dohazari]], southeast of Chittagong. The plan was to reach Satkania, Dulahazra, Chakarin, Edgaon, Ramu and Cox's Bazar, with four major river bridges and a 28&nbsp;km branch from Ramu to Gundum. In 2013, the [[Chittagong Circular Railway]] was completed.\n\nIn 2015, construction of a 15&nbsp;km branch to [[Agartala]], [[Tripura]] in [[Northeast India]] commenced.<ref>{{cite news|title=Work on new India-Bangladesh railway link from 2015|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Work-on-new-India-Bangladesh-railway-link-from-2015/articleshow/36725087.cms|accessdate=7 December 2014|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=Jun 17, 2014}}</ref> In 2017, land acquisition took place to facilitate the construction.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/rail-project-to-connect-india-and-bangladesh-begins-land-acquisition-notices-served-to-257-families-3873163.html|title=Rail project to connect India and Bangladesh begins; land acquisition notices served to 257 families|date=2017-07-30|work=Firstpost|access-date=2017-08-17}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nFrom the end of the [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] in 1971 until 1982, the railway was governed by a Railway Board. It then came under the Railway Division of the Ministry of Communications. The Director General of the railway was the Secretary of the Railway Division of the Ministry of Communications. In 1995, governance of the railway was assumed by the \"Bangladesh Railway Authority\" which was chaired by the Minister of Railways.<ref name=\"brorg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mor.gov.bd/ |title=Ministry of Railways-Government of the People's Republic of Bangladesh &#124; \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u09aa\u09a5 \u09ae\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09a3\u09be\u09b2\u09af\u09bc-\u0997\u09a3\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09c0 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0 |website=Mor.gov.bd |date=2016-02-28 |accessdate=2016-08-07}}</ref> Inspections are made by an external government authority.\n\nThe features of Bangladesh Railway include the usage of several gauges and the division of the rail system by the [[Jamuna River (Bangladesh)|Jamuna River]], Brahmaputra into the Western Zone and the Eastern Zone of operations. Crossing the river is one bridge, the Jamuna Bridge which was completed in 2003.\n\nThe East Zone and the West Zone each have a General Manager who answers to the Director General of the Railway Authority. Each zone has its own raft of departments for operation, maintenance, and finances. Each zone is divided into two divisions with departments for personnel, transportation, commercial, finance mechanical, way and works signalling, telecommunication, electrical and medical services.\n\nThe East Zone has a workshop division in [[Pahartali Thana|Pahartali]]. The West Zone's workshop division is in [[Saidpur, Rajshahi Division|Saidpur]]. The railway has a central locomotive workshop for broad and metre gauge locomotives in [[Parbatipur Upazila|Parbatipur]]. It also has a Railway Training Academy.<ref name=brorg/> There is are diesel workshops in Pahartali, Dhaka and Parbatipur. Maintenance on coaches and wagons is carried out at the \"C and W\" shop in Saidpur, [[Nilphamari]] and at the \"C and W\" shop Pahartali.\n\n==Rolling stock==\n===Locomotives===\n{{main|Locomotives of Bangladesh}}\n\n====Diesel====\n[[File:BR 2934.jpg|thumb|[[Bangladesh Railway Class 2900]] locomotive]]\nBangladesh Railway's fleet of [[diesel locomotive]]s includes both diesel-electric and diesel-hydraulic machines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railway.gov.bd/rolling_stock.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-09-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830132319/http://www.railway.gov.bd/rolling_stock.asp |archivedate=30 August 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> In 2007, there were 77 broad gauge diesel-electric locomotives. In 2012, Bangladesh Railway ordered 16 new broad gauge locomotives of 3100&nbsp;hp from [[Diesel Locomotive Works]], India.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.globalrailnews.com/2012/08/28/dlw-bags-order-for-16-locomotives-from-bangladesh-railways/|title = DLW bags order for 16 locomotives from Bangladesh Railways|date = 28 August 2012|access-date = 28 August 2017|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170828062624/https://www.globalrailnews.com/2012/08/28/dlw-bags-order-for-16-locomotives-from-bangladesh-railways/|archive-date = 28 August 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref> There were also 208 metre gauge diesel-electric locomotives including those of classes [[Bangladesh Railway Class 2000|2000]], [[Bangladesh Railway Class 2600|2600]], [[Bangladesh Railway Class 2700|2700]], and [[Bangladesh Railway Class 2900|2900]]. The total number was 285.\n\nIn 2019, 40 EMD GT42ACLs were ordered from [[Progress Rail Services]].<ref>[https://www.railwayage.com/mechanical/locomotives/bangladesh-taps-progress-rail-for-gt-series-power/?RAchannel=news Bangladesh taps Progress Rail for GT Series power] ''[[Railway Age]]'' 2 July 2019</ref>\n\n====Steam====\nA small number of [[steam locomotive]]s are preserved in Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.internationalsteam.co.uk/trains/bangladesh01.htm |title=Preserved Steam Locomotives in Bangladesh |publisher=Internationalsteam.co.uk |accessdate=2016-08-06}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Location\n! Builder\n! Wheel<br />arrangement\n! Gauge\n|-\n| Dhaka Railway HQ\n| [[Nippon Sharyo|Nippon]]\n| [[2-8-2]]\n| Metre gauge\n|-\n| Saidpur Works\n| [[W. G. Bagnall]]\n| [[2-4-0]]T\n| {{RailGauge|2ft 6in}}\n|-\n| Saidpur Works\n| [[Vulcan Foundry]]\n| [[0-6-0]]\n| {{RailGauge|5ft 6in}}\n|-\n| Paksey Railway HQ\n| Vulcan Foundry?\n| [[2-4-0]]T\n| {{RailGauge|2ft 6in}}\n|}\n\nThe 762&nbsp;mm gauge locomotives are from the Rupsa {{ndash}} [[Bagerhat District|Bagerhat]] railway which was the only 762&nbsp;mm gauge line in East Pakistan in 1947. It was changed to 1,676&nbsp;mm gauge in 1970.\n\n=== Diesel-electric Multiple Unit ===\n[[File:Bangladesh Railway, Komlapur Railway Station.jpg|thumb|A DEMU train at Kamalapur Railway Station, Dhaka]]\nDiesel-electric Multiple Unit (DEMU) trains first started their journey in Bangladesh with the introduction of Dhaka-Narayangonj Commuter train on 24th April, 2013<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bangla.bdnews24.com/economy/article1644488.bdnews|title=\u099a\u09c0\u09a8\u09be \u09a1\u09c7\u09ae\u09c1 \u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a8 \u0986\u09b0 \u0995\u09bf\u09a8\u09ac\u09c7 \u09a8\u09be \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0|last=\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a4\u09bf\u09ac\u09c7\u09a6\u0995|first=\u099c\u09cd\u09af\u09c7\u09b7\u09cd\u09a0|last2=\u09a1\u099f\u0995\u09ae|first2=\u09ac\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09a8\u09bf\u0989\u099c \u099f\u09cb\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09a8\u09cd\u099f\u09bf\u09ab\u09cb\u09b0|website=bangla.bdnews24.com|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>. Total 20 sets of meter-gauge DEMU were manufactured by [[CRRC Tangshan|Tangshan Railway Vehicle Co Ltd]], China<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newagebd.net/article/78743/pm-opposes-import-of-demu-train|title=PM opposes import of DEMU train|website=New Age {{!}} The Most Popular Outspoken English Daily in Bangladesh|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>. Each set comprises of three units. Total 300 passengers can board a set, 149 by sitting and 151 by standing<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/302844/DEMU-train-becomes-burden-on-railway|title=DEMU train becomes burden on railway|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>. They are rated 460 hp and can run up to 20 km distance with a maximum speed of 80 km/h. They have a life-span of 30 years<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newagebd.net/article/78743/pm-opposes-import-of-demu-train|title=PM opposes import of DEMU train|website=New Age {{!}} The Most Popular Outspoken English Daily in Bangladesh|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>. Currently only 9 of 20 sets are active<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prothomalo.com/bangladesh/article/1443641|title=\u09a1\u09c7\u09ae\u09c1 \u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a8\u09c7\u09b0 \u099a\u09be\u09aa\u09c7 \u09ac\u09c7\u09b8\u09be\u09ae\u09be\u09b2 \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2|website=\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a5\u09ae \u0986\u09b2\u09cb|language=bn|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>.\n\n==Freight and cargo services==\nAs a national carrier, Bangladesh Railway is obliged to carry essential commodities such as grain and fertiliser to remote parts of Bangladesh at discounted rates. Bangladesh Railway transports containers from the [[Port of Chittagong]] to Dhaka Inland Container Depot, where there are [[customs]] facilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cpa.gov.bd/facilities-of-cpa/|title=Facilities of CPA \u2013 Chittagong Port Authority|website=cpa.gov.bd|access-date=20 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512173236/http://cpa.gov.bd/facilities-of-cpa/|archive-date=12 May 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> The rolling stock to carry containers was manufactured from existing stock. On 5 August 1991, a container-only train came into service. A goods train operates from [[Singhabad]] and [[Petrapole]], India to Rohanpur and [[Benapole]], Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://twocircles.net/2011sep21/india_approves_new_railway_link_bangladesh.html|title=India approves new railway link with Bangladesh |website=twocircles.net |access-date=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Accidents ===\n* On July 10, 2014, a major freight train accident occurred near [[Faujdarhat Railway Station]] at 6.30 am. A freight train from [[Patenga]] was carrying furnace oil to a power plant, but near Faujdarhat the train derailed and leaked around {{convert|21255|impgal|abbr=on}} of furnace oil. Six wagons of the train derailed and oil from three of the wagons flowed into a nearby canal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oil-laden train derails in Ctg|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/oil-laden-train-derails-in-ctg-32674|website=the daily star}}</ref>\n* On September 14, 2016, a freight train derailed in the [[Faujdarhat]] area. The loco driver and the assistant driver were injured.<ref>{{cite web|title=Home Bangladesh 2 injured in Ctg rail engine derailment|url=http://en.prothomalo.com/bangladesh/news/120877/2-injured-in-Ctg-rail-engine-derailment|website=prothom alo}}</ref>\n\n==Passenger services==\n[[File:Jamuna Express.jpg|thumb|Jamuna Express at Kamalapur station]]\n[[File:Parabat Express.jpg|thumb|Parabat Express at Sylhet station]] \nRailway is a principal mode of transport in Bangladesh. In the 2005 financial year, 42 million passengers travelled on the Bangladesh Railway.<ref name=stores>{{cite web|url=http://www.railway.gov.bd/stores.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091207001418/http://www.railway.gov.bd/stores.asp |archivedate=7 December 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> Inter-city services, contribute to over seventy percent of Bangladesh Railway's revenue.<ref name=stores /> In 2014, the railway owned 312 broad gauge coaches and 1,164 metre gauge coaches.<ref name=\"adb.org\"/>\n\nIn 2017, Bangladesh Railway operated 90 inter-city trains (up & down), 52 mail or express trains, 64 commuter trains ([[Diesel Multiple Unit|DEMU]]), 135 shuttle or local trains and 2 international services.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://railway.portal.gov.bd/site/page/e35cebe7-3b39-46be-ae6b-f267d4d1375f |script-title=bn:\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b0 \u09af\u09be\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09c0\u09ac\u09be\u09b9\u09c0 \u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a8|website=railway.portal.gov.bd |language=bn |access-date=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nTwo times per week, a passenger train operates a service to India. In April 2008, the [[Maitri Express]] between Dhaka and [[Kolkata]] came into operation on the Gede {{ndash}} Darsana route.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view//bangladesh-india-order-reopens.html | title=Bangladesh \u2013 India border reopens | work=[[Railway Gazette International]] | date=5 August 2007 }}</ref> On 9 November 2017, a new weekly train, the [[Bandhan Express]], came into operation between [[Khulna]] and Kolkata via Petrapole and Benapole (172&nbsp;km).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/pf_story.php?nid%3D50807 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-09-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518212137/http://www.thedailystar.net/pf_story.php?nid=50807 |archivedate=18 May 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nTickets for Bangladesh Railway services are available at all stations. Most stations are computerised and tickets which can be purchased within four days of departure, are printed. Full refunds (excluding clerical charges) are available up until two days before departure. The railway reserves ten percent of tickets for online sales. Of these tickets, fifteen percent are reserved for mobile phone sales.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://techthumbs.com/how-to-buy-bangladesh-railwaytrain-ticket-online|title=How to Buy Bangladesh Railway(Train) Ticket Online|date=2012-10-13|work=Tech Thumbs|access-date=2017-08-17}}</ref>\n\n===Accidents===\n* On 11 July 2006, a train collided with a crowded bus at an unmanned railroad crossing at [[Akkelpur Upazila]], Jaipurhat District. Thirty-three people died and thirty were injured.\n* On 13 October 2007, the rear carriages of the Probhati Express derailed near Dhaka. Four people died and fifty were injured.\n* On 16 April 2008, a Dinajpur {{ndash}} Dhaka Ekota express train collided with a local bus on a level crossing on the outskirts of Kalihati, [[Tangail District]]. Eighteen people died and thirty were injured.\n* On 14 May 2008, an Upaban express train crashed into the rear of a [[Noakhali]] express train at [[Ashuganj Upazila|the Ashuganj Upazila]] station, [[Brahmanbaria District]]. Eight people died and one hundred were injured.\n* On 8 December 2010, a collision between two passenger trains killed at least ten people.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.railwaysafrica.com/blog/2010/12/fatal-bangladesh-collision/ |title=Fatal Bangladesh Collision |date=12 December 2010 |website=Railways Africa |accessdate=12 December 2010}}</ref>\n* On 23 June 2019, several bogies of Dhaka-bound Upaban Express train from Sylhet veered off the tracks at around 11:40 pm after a culvert over the Barochhara Canal broke down, 200 yards off Baramchal Railway Station. At least five people died and hundreds were injured. Locals who worked overnight with the first responders claimed at least 10-15 people have been killed.<ref>{{cite web |date=24 June 2019 |title=Bangladesh: 5 killed as four train coaches derail, hundreds injured |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/world/story/bangladesh-5-killed-as-four-train-coaches-derail-hundreds-injured-1554855-2019-06-24 |work=India Today}}</ref>\n* On 12 November 2019, At least 16 passengers died and score other injured as Dhaka-bound Turna Nishita Express rammed Chattogram-bound Udayan Express from Sylhet at Mandobagh Railway Station in Kasba.[http://epaper.thedailystar.net/index.php?opt=view&page=1&date=2019-11-13 Train Driver's Fault' Takes Sixteen Lives]\n* On 14 November 2019, Two days after a deadly train crash in Brahmanbaria, Rangpur Express, bound from Dhaka to Rangpur, braced an accident at Ullapara station in Sirajganj at around 2pm on Thursday. Seven compartments of Rangpur Express, including its engine and power car, derailed in the Ullapara Railway Station area and a fire broke out in three of its compartments.\n\n===Accommodation classes===\nBangladesh Railway has three main passenger classes, \"Air conditioned\", \"First\" and \"Second\". Most trains do not provide the \"Air conditioned\" class. On inter-city and long-distance trains, a restaurant car and a power car are included at the centre of the train. All inter-city trains are partially air-conditioned, feature padded leather seats and provide passengers with on-demand sheets, pillows, blankets, as well as meals in a dining car. Some diesel{{ndash}}electric trains provider commuter services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://railway.portal.gov.bd/site/page/e35cebe7-3b39-46be-ae6b-f267d4d1375f/%25E0%25A6%25AF%25E0%25A6%25BE%25E0%25A6%25A4%25E0%25A7%258D%25E0%25A6%25B0%25E0%25A7%2580%25E0%25A6%25AC%25E0%25A6%25BE%25E0%25A6%25B9%25E0%25A7%2580-%25E0%25A6%259F%25E0%25A7%258D%25E0%25A6%25B0%25E0%25A7%2587%25E0%25A6%25A8|script-title=bn:\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b0\u09c7\u09b2\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b0 \u09af\u09be\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09c0\u09ac\u09be\u09b9\u09c0 \u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a8|website=railway.portal.gov.bd|language=bn|access-date=20 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324214752/http://railway.portal.gov.bd/site/page/e35cebe7-3b39-46be-ae6b-f267d4d1375f/%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%A4%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%80%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B9%E0%A7%80-%E0%A6%9F%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%A8|archive-date=24 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"border:1px solid black;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Class\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Description\n|-\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:20%;\"| '''Tapanukul ({{lang|bn|\u09a4\u09be\u09aa\u09be\u09a8\u09c1\u0995\u09c2\u09b2}})''' <br> '''First class AC'''\n| valign=\"top\" | This is the most expensive class. This air-conditioned coach is used only on popular Inter-City routes. The coaches are carpeted, have sleeping accommodation, ample leg room and have privacy features like personal coupes.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |'''First class ({{lang|bn|\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a5\u09ae \u09b6\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a3\u09c0}})'''\n| valign=\"top\" | This class is relatively luxurious, but not air-conditioned; has sleeping berths, and ample leg room.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''First class Chair<br> ({{lang|bn|\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a5\u09ae \u09b6\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a3\u09c0 \u099a\u09c7\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0}})'''\n| valign=\"top\" | Chair car or day coach with a total of five seats in a row on broad gauge trains and four seats in a row on metre gauge trains, used for daily travel.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''2nd Class-Shovon Chair<br> ({{lang|bn|\u09e8\u09af\u09bc \u09b6\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a3\u09c0-\u09b6\u09cb\u09ad\u09a8 \u099a\u09c7\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0}}) '''\n| valign=\"top\" | The 2nd Class Shovon Chair is basically a chair car preferred by most middle-class passengers. Has a total of five seats in a row on broad gauge trains and four seats in a row on metre gauge trains.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''2nd Class-Shovon<br> ({{lang|bn|\u09e8\u09af\u09bc \u09b6\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a3\u09c0-\u09b6\u09cb\u09ad\u09a8}}) '''\n| valign=\"top\" |  One of the cheapest classes; seats are not very comfortable.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''2nd Class-Shulov<br> ({{lang|bn|\u09e8\u09af\u09bc \u09b6\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09a3\u09c0- \u09b8\u09c1\u09b2\u09ad}}) '''\n| valign=\"top\" | The cheapest accommodation, with seats made of pressed wood or steel and are cushioned. Only found in sub-urban and short-distance routes. Although entry into the compartment is guaranteed, a seat is not guaranteed. These coaches are usually very crowded.\n|}\n\n==List of railway stations in Bangladesh==\n[[Kamalapur Railway Station]] is the central railway station in Dhaka. In 2015, Bangladesh Railway serviced 489 railway stations. These include one block hut, thirteen train halts, and four goods booking points. The schedule of Bangladesh Railway has changed 26 Trains in the new year 2020. The East zone Train schedule will active on 10 January 2020<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bdteletalk.com/bangladesh-railway-schedule-time// |title=Bangladesh Railway Schedule, Time table |date=3 January 2020 |website=Bdteletalk.com |accessdate=3 January 2020}}</ref>.\n\nHere is a list of railway stations in Bangladesh district-wise:\n\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| image1 = Kamalapur Railway Station 4.jpg\n| caption1 = Kamalapur Railway Station\n| width1 = 200\n| image2 = Kamlan.jpg\n| caption2 = Kamalapur railway station at night\n| width2 = 200\n| image3 = \n| caption3 = Khulna railway station\n| width3 = 200\n| image4 = Rajshahi Railway Station 01.JPG\n| caption4 = Rajshahi railway station\n| width4 = 200\n| image5 = Sylhet Railway.jpg\n| caption5 = Sylhet Railway Station\n| width5 = 200\n| image6 = Parbatipur_Railway_Junction.JPG\n| caption6 = Parbatipur Railway Junction Station at Dinajpur District.\n| width6 = 200\n| image7 = Noapara.jpg\n| caption7 = Noapara Railway Station at Jessore District.\n| width7 = 200\n| width8 = 200\n| image9 = Tongi Railway Station, Bangladesh.JPG\n| caption9 = Tongi Railway Station, Dhaka\n| width9 = 200\n| image10 = Railway Airport.jpg\n| caption10 = Airport Railway Station\n| width10 = 200\n| total_width = \n| alt1 = \n}}\n\n=== Bogura ===\n\n# [[Santahar railway station|Santahar Junction Railway Station]]\n\n=== Brahmanbaria ===\n\n# Akhaura Junction Railway Station\n#Ashugonj Railway Station\n#Brahmanbaria Railway Station\n#Gangashagor Railway Station\n#Imambari Railway Station\n#Kosba Railway Station\n#Mondobag Railway Station\n#Paghachang Railway Station\n#Shaldandi Railway Station\n#Shashidol Railway Station\n#Talshohor Railway Station\n#Vatshala Railway Station\n\n=== Chandpur ===\n\n# Bolakhal Railway Station\n# [[Chandpur Railway Station]]\n# Chandpur Court Railway Station\n# Chitoshi Road Railway Station\n# Hajigonj 